With Hamas releasing all 20 living Israeli captives in Gaza and Israel freeing Palestinian prisoners in the occupied West Bank

The Gaza Strip has been reduced to a grey wasteland of rubble after Israeli forces launched an extensive military campaign in response to the October 7th Hamas attacks. More than 67,000 Palestinians have been killed, with tens of thousands of bodies believed to remain buried beneath the ruins. Critical infrastructure, such as Al Shifa Hospital, has been obliterated, leaving Gaza's medical system in tatters.
Israel is now facing genocide charges at the International Court of Justice, brought by South Africa. The accusations are supported by a UN-backed commission and international scholars who cite overwhelming evidence of systematic violence, including the targeting of shelters, places of worship, and humanitarian aid sites. He said the 20-point peace plan would form the foundation for a “great and lasting peace,” calling for Gaza’s staged demilitarisation and large-scale reconstruction.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
A fragile ceasefire in Gaza has brought the release of the remaining 20 Israeli captives held by Hamas, alongside Israel’s release of nearly 2,000 Palestinian prisoners and detainees. 
Families on both sides have been reunited amid scenes of anticipation and celebration in Tel Aviv, Gaza, and the occupied West Bank. 
For many, this moment marks the culmination of years of suffering and political tension surrounding the captive crisis.
While Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu hailed the development as a triumph and praised US President Donald Trump’s role in mediation, reactions in Gaza remain mixed. 
Amid relief at the pause in airstrikes and the arrival of aid, there is also anger and grief over the sustained devastation. 
This deal—brokered through intense international mediation led by the US, Egypt, and Qatar—has raised hopes for peace, but its long-term significance remains uncertain. 
For Palestinians, the focus is on immediate survival rather than lasting resolutions.

Yasser Abu Azzoum, a Palestinian in Gaza whose 23-year-old son Mohammed is set to be released from Israeli prison today, says the feeling is “indescribable”.

“I’m not able to speak properly because I am overwhelmed with joy,” he told Al Jazeera in Khan Younis.

“I was arrested along with my son from the same shelter in 2023. I haven’t seen him in two years. My joy today is much greater than it was on the day I was released.”

Abu Azzoum said his wife gave birth to another child while his elder son was in prison.

“We will be reunited and will spend the rest of our days in joy,” he added.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Palestinian groups have released the first round of living Israeli captives held in Gaza, as agreed under the ceasefire deal with Israel. 
Seven captives have been handed over to the Red Cross, who will facilitate their transfer to Israeli forces.
They are expected to undergo an initial medical examination before arriving at Reim military base in southern Israel, where they will reunite with their families for the first time in more than two years. 

The first hand over was celebrated by emotional crowds, including families of the Israeli captives in what's known as Hostages Square in Tel Aviv.
That's where Israelis have been protesting every week since the war began.
Many of them have accused Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of sabotaging and delaying previous attempts to reach a deal to secure their release. 

Al Jazeera’s Nour Odeh is following developments in Israel from Jordan's capital.
